; LLM instructions (read this first before editing)
    ; General
        ;------------------------------------------------------------------------------
        ; AoE2 AI SCRIPTING REFERENCE FOR THIS FILE (read before editing)
        ;------------------------------------------------------------------------------
        ; This file uses classic .per rule syntax together with UserPatch-style extended
        ; AI commands. Keep edits within that model.
        ;
        ; Core syntax
        ; - ';' starts a comment and comments run to the end of the line.
        ; - (defconst <name> <number>) gives a readable name to a numeric ID.
        ; - Rules are written as:
        ;       (defrule
        ;           <facts / conditions>
        ;       =>
        ;           <actions>
        ;       )
        ; - Facts/conditions go before '=>'. Actions go after '=>'.
        ;
        ; Goal handling
        ; - Goals are script variables addressed by numeric goal IDs.
        ; - Use (set-goal <goal> <value>) to set a goal directly.
        ; - Use up-compare-goal / up-modify-goal when reading, comparing, or doing math
        ;   with goal values.
        ; - Prefix meaning in UserPatch goal math:
        ;       c:  literal constant
        ;       g:  another goal's stored value
        ;       s:  a strategic number value
        ; - IMPORTANT: when a comparison or assignment should use the VALUE stored in a
        ;   goal, use goal-aware syntax such as g:<, g:>, g:=, g:+, g:-, etc. Without
        ;   goal-aware syntax, the script treats the symbol as its constant ID instead of
        ;   the value currently stored inside that goal.
        ;
        ; Point and search handling
        ; - up-get-point / up-copy-point / up-set-target-point treat the supplied '-x'
        ;   goal as the start of a consecutive (x,y) pair. Therefore every '-x' goal must
        ;   have a matching '-y' goal defined immediately after it, even if the '-y' goal
        ;   is never referenced explicitly elsewhere in the code.
        ; - (up-get-search-state <first-goal>) writes four consecutive goals in this
        ;   exact order: local-total, local-last, remote-total, remote-last.
        ; - Search lists are mutable. Reset or rebuild them deliberately before reusing
        ;   search-local or search-remote for a different task.
        ;
        ; File-local conventions
        ; - All goals start with 'gl-'.
        ; - Global temp goals use IDs 41-99.
        ; - Module-local temp goals use IDs 10000-16000 and must end with '__#xxx'.
        ; - Non-temp goals do not use the module suffix and must never overlap.
        ; - Rule ID storage goals are always non-temp.
        ; - Coordinate pairs must be consecutive and define '-x' first and '-y' second.
        ; - If indirect goals are used as a scratch array, reserve a contiguous block for
        ;   them and do not place unrelated temp goals inside that reserved range.
        ;------------------------------------------------------------------------------
    ; Goal constans 
        ; <LLM's should read this entire section and follow its instructions>
            ; Proper naming and numbering of goal constants is a vital part of both readability and functionality. 
            ; Thus whenever being asked to rename or restructure goal constants any LLM must addhere to these rules:

            ; 1. All goals must start with "gl-"

            ; 2. All goals ending in "-x" or "-y" are coordinate goal pairs. (this also includes goals with a "__#xxx" suffix after the "-x" or "-y")
            ; The constants for these to goals MUST be consecutive and their constants MUST be above 40.
            ; Coordinate goals MUST ALLWAYS have their partner goal be defined with a seperate consecutive constant and the "-x" goal must always have the lower constant number.

            ; 3. The command (up-get-search-state gl-local-total) will set values for these four goals that MUST be consecutive: 
            ; gl-local-total, gl-local-last, gl-remote-total, gl-remote-last. 
            
            ; 4. Goals are split up into temporary and non-temporary goals. 
            ; Temporary goals are local to a certain module of the code and can be changed freely outside this module. 
            ; Non-temporary goals cannot be changed outside their module.
            ; In order to ensure readability and avoid overlapping of goal constants temporary goals local to a certain module must use goal values from 10000 to 16000.
            ; These module temp-goals also needs a "__#xxx" suffix where xxx is nr of that module to avoid overlapping naming in goal constants.
            ; A few temp goals like gl-temp are global and thus won't have a __#xxx suffix. These only use goal value constants from 41-99
            ; While module temp goals are defined in the beginning of that module other goals specific to that module will be defined in the start of the script together with other non-temp goals.
            ; They will have their own sections for clarity though.
            ; Non-temp goals do not use the module suffix.
            ; Global non-temp goals must use goal constant values from 100-999
            ; Rule id's are ALLWAYS non-temp goals.
            ; While the goal constant values of temp-goals can freely overlap goal constant values of non-temp goals can NEVER overlap.

            ; 5. Goal names must be short, readable and precise. 
            ; Do not change goal names without instructions to do so.
            ; If a goal name seems unnessesary long or unprecise feel free to suggest a better name, but don't change it without permission.
            ; Abreviations in goal names are welcome, as long as they are readable, self explanatory and cannot be confused with other abreviations.
            ; Goal names are written in english.

            ; </LLM's should read this entire section and follow its instructions>
        


